            },
            {
                "name": "Zombie",
                "boxing_ring_title": "Night Roamer",
                "type": "Different character"
            },
            {
                "name": "Enderman",
                "boxing_ring_title": "End Dweller",
                "type": "Different character"
            }
        ],
        "tips": [
            {
                "title": "In Their Series",
                "content": "Steve and Alex are two of the many incarnations of the player when they venture into the Minecraft world. Explore dungeons, create buildings, or trade with villagers—the adventure is in your hands!",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Zombies from the Series",
                "content": "The P7 appearance is the Zombie, known to appear from the darkness and attack people. Fortunately, the Zombies in Minecraft catch fire when they touch sunlight, burning away after a bit.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Enderman from the Series",
                "content": "The P8 appearance is the Enderman, one of the residents of the End. They like to teleport about, quietly carrying blocks. However, if you lock eyes with one, it will turn into a strong enemy and attack you!",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Tools and Moves",
                "content": "You'll make use of a sword, axe, shovel, or pickaxe, depending on which move you use. Each tool will break after some use, which will reduce the power of any attack that uses that tool.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Materials and Moves",
                "content": "Materials are necessary for the moves Steve brings to the battle. If you don't have the needed materials, the move will be weaker than normal or even fail outright! Keep track of the materials you have on hand.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Mine (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "Hold the button down, and you can dig for materials below you or in nearby walls. The speed that you mine and what materials you uncover changes depending on where you are mining.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Mineable Materials (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "In order of easiest to hardest to obtain, you can mine dirt, wood, stone, iron, redstone, gold, and diamond. Depending on the ground in the stage, you might dig up ice, sand, or wool instead of dirt.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "High-Quality Mineable Materials (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "Iron, gold, redstone, and diamonds can be obtained from any kind of surface.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Mining and the Material Gauge (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "Some of the materials you collect will be shown as a gauge near your damage. However, gold and diamond will be displayed separately, and redstone won't be displayed at all.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Quality of Mined Material (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "The harder the walls and floors are, the better the quality of the materials you'll mine. However, it will also take longer to dig up those materials.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Mining Limits (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "There is a limit on how much of each material you can carry, and the rarer the material, the less of it you can hold. Any material you dig up beyond the limit will be discarded.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Mining Tools (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "You use different tools depending on the type of wall or ground you're digging into. These tools help you mine faster, and when one breaks, it'll slow down how quickly you can mine.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Mining, Tools, and Quality (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "There are five levels of quality for the various tools: diamond, gold, iron, stone, and wood. Generally, a higher-quality material is more durable and allows you to mine faster, though gold has its own properties.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "While Mining (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "While mining, you can jump or move forward or backward, but you won't be able to attack. If you move forward or backward, you'll keep on mining, but jumping will cancel the action.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Mining on Battlefield-Form Stages (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "All of the Battlefield-form and Ω-form stages have the same amounts of the various materials available for mining.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Craft (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "While in front of the crafting table, pressing the special-move button will use the materials you have to create, upgrade, or repair tools.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Crafting Tools (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "Use the crafting table when you have a broken tool, and you'll craft the highest-quality tool with the materials available automatically. If this is an improvement on your other tools, they'll all be upgraded too!",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Using Craft to Upgrade (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "If you have the materials to make a higher-quality tool, use Craft to create the upgraded tool. In fact, all tools will upgrade at the same time.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Using Craft to Repair (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "You can repair damaged tools by using the same materials that they were crafted with. This is much quicker than crafting a new tool after one breaks.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Canceling Craft (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "The move can be canceled by jumping, shielding, dodging, or pressing the attack button. You won't lose material if you cancel Craft this way.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Crafting with Gold (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "Gold tools break easier than ones made from any other material, but they are also the quickest to mine with and the quickest for unleashing moves.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Crafting with Diamond (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "Diamond tools are very powerful, but it takes longer to craft them than it does to craft tools using the other materials.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Moving the Crafting Table (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "Press the special-move button while shielding to use some materials and reposition your crafting table nearby. Moving the crafting table will use material in the following order: wood, stone, then iron.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Using Create Block (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "If you press the special-move button in the air, you'll use your materials to create and place a block at your feet. Holding down the button and moving or jumping will continuously place blocks.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Materials and Create Block (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "You create blocks from the materials you've mined, starting with dirt, then wood, then stone, and finally iron. The different materials all have different durabilities.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Block Limits (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "There is a limit on how many blocks you can place at one time. Once you've reached the limit, each new block you create will cause the oldest block you placed to go away.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Block Rules (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "You cannot place blocks near the edge of the screen. If a block you created starts flashing, this means it is close to that limit.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Overlapping Blocks (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "If you use this move in a spot where you've already placed a block, the old block will be destroyed and you can place a new one.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Destroying Blocks (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "As time passes, blocks placed with Create Block will eventually break. Being hit by attacks, stood on by fighters, or hit from below will cause the blocks to break faster.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Mining Blocks (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "It is possible to mine blocks you've placed, but this will only break the block and not yield any materials.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Creating Blocks while Mining (Neutral Special)",
                "content": "If you are mining and jump, you'll instead jump and place a block at your feet.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Minecart (Side Special)",
                "content": "Place rails and charge forward while riding in an iron minecart. If you jump, you'll leap out of the minecart, but it will continue forward. The first opponent caught in its path will be carried away.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Stuck in the Minecart (Side Special)",
                "content": "The more damage a fighter has taken, the longer they'll be carried along in the minecart. Trapped fighters can move the control stick back and forth to help escape the minecart faster.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Using Minecart Repeatedly (Side Special)",
                "content": "You can use the minecart repeatedly, but doing so will reduce the amount of time a fighter is trapped in it.",
                "level": "Intermediate"
            },
            {
                "title": "Minecart on a Hill (Side Special)",
                "content": "If the minecart tries to go uphill, it will slow down, stop, and even roll backward. However, if the minecart is going downhill, it will actually speed up!",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Minecart and Powered Rails (Side Special)",
                "content": "If you've collected gold and redstone, you can place powered rails. This will increase the speed of the minecart and also allow it to go up hills!",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Charge with Minecart and Powered Rail (Side Special)",
                "content": "Use the special-move button while riding the minecart to place powered rails and speed up. Don't forget that this only works if you've mined up redstone and gold.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Reboarding the Minecart (Side Special)",
                "content": "It's possible to get back in the minecart after you've jumped out, but you can do this only twice. Keep track of how many times you've jumped out!",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Minecart Controls (Side Special)",
                "content": "Push left or right on the control stick to send the minecart rolling in that direction, placing rails along the way. Once you run out of materials and fall off the rails, the minecart will come to a stop.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Materials for Rails (Side Special)",
                "content": "In order to place rails, you'll need to collect the required materials. Easy-to-obtain materials, like dirt, will be used first. After that, you'll use wood, stone, and then iron.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Destroying the Minecart (Side Special)",
                "content": "The minecart won't last forever! After taking a certain amount of damage, the minecart will break. If Steve was the one who broke it, he'll be able to collect iron.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Elytra (Up Special)",
                "content": "Elytra will allow you to glide sideways. Tilt the stick up and down while gliding to adjust the angle and trajectory of the glide.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Elytra and Firework Rocket (Up Special)",
                "content": "At the beginning of the move, the firework rocket ignites to increase your speed. You can damage any opponents you hit while the speed increase is active.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Cancel Elytra (Up Special)",
                "content": "You can cancel Elytra midflight by dodging or attacking while gliding. You'll fall downward after doing so, but you'll be able to move left or right a little as you fall.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Elytra's Time Limit (Up Special)",
                "content": "After a certain period of time, the elytra will automatically fall off, and you'll fall downward. Be careful when this happens, as you'll be vulnerable to attacks as you fall.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Crashing with Elytra (Up Special)",
                "content": "While using the fireworks rocket, you won't crash into terrain and go into a free fall. However, once the rocket is out of fuel, hitting a ceiling or wall will send you falling, so be careful.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "TNT (Down Special)",
                "content": "This move uses a lot of materials to create and place a powerful TNT block and a pressure plate. The block will explode after some time, if the block takes some damage, or if someone steps on the pressure plate.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "TNT Materials (Down Special)",
                "content": "The easier to obtain materials will be used first when making the TNT block. While the power doesn't change depending on the materials, the block can be made with fewer rare materials.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Remote TNT Detonation (Down Special)",
                "content": "When on the ground, if you continue to hold the special-move button you can walk and place a redstone circuit. Release the button to create a pressure plate, which you can attack or step on to set off the TNT.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Several TNT Blocks (Down Special)",
                "content": "If you place your own TNT block next to another player's TNT block, stepping on the pressure plate will set off both blocks.",
                "level": "Intermediate"
            },
            {
                "title": "TNT Explosion (Down Special)",
                "content": "TNT doesn't see a difference between friend and foe. Stand too close, and the explosion from your own TNT will still hurt you! Be sure to place your pressure plate at a safe distance.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "TNT's Power (Down Special)",
                "content": "Using a pressure plate to set off a TNT block will increase the amount of damage the explosion does compared to waiting a while or damaging the block.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "House of Boom (Final Smash)",
                "content": "Create a large piston to launch multiple opponents to the side. One unlucky foe will get trapped in a dark room—filled with enemies and explosives—which quickly explodes.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Neutral Attack / Side Tilt Attack",
                "content": "You can hold down the attack button to continuously swing the sword. You can also move while continuing to attack!",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Flint and Steel (Down Tilt Attack)",
                "content": "If you use this move near the edge, the fire you create will fall down, damaging opponents below or making it difficult for someone to get back to the stage.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Air Attacks with a Sword",
                "content": "Swing a sword in the air by jumping while pressing the attack button. Using neutral attack while jumping will leave you less vulnerable to enemy attacks.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Pickaxe Attacks (Forward Air Attack / Back Air Attack)",
                "content": "Your forward and back air attacks will make use of the pickaxe, and there is a small opportunity to cause a meteor effect while swinging the pickaxe in the forward air attack.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Anvil (Down Air Attack)",
                "content": "Create an iron anvil and drop it to attack below you. The anvil will vanish after a short time, but you can stand on top of it until it does.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Fishing Rod (Grab Attack)",
                "content": "This move cannot be used in the air, but if you hook an opponent on the ground, you'll capture them in a fence.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            },
            {
                "title": "Downward Throw",
                "content": "The downward throw will slam an opponent into the ground, and if you have iron, this will set your opponent up perfectly for the anvil that gets dropped on them.",
                "level": "Beginner"
            }
        ],
        "fighters": [
            {
                "id": "77",
                "name": "Steve",
                "slug": "steve",
                "also_appears_in": []
            }
        ]
    },
